50|$|Flat-panel Volume CT is a {{technique}} under development to make computed tomography images with improved performance (in particular, with improved spatial resolution). The key difference between volume CT and traditional CT is that volume CT uses a two-dimensional <b>x-ray</b> <b>detector</b> orientation (usually in a square panel orientation), to take multiple two-dimensional images. On the other hand, the conventional CT uses a one-dimensional <b>x-ray</b> <b>detector</b> orientation (a row of detectors) to take one-dimensional x-ray images.|$|E
